{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T17:52:16.800Z",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Modern language models are stacks of layers built from millions of simple units that transform vectors of numbers. Understanding neurons and layers is the first step from \"black-box LLM\" to the concrete math that powers embeddings, attention, and next-token prediction."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "artificial neuron",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (or unit) takes a vector of inputs, computes a weighted sum plus a bias, and passes the result to an activation function. A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "layer",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a group of neurons that share the same input and produce a vector output. Stacking layers creates a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "feedforward neural network",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": input layer → one or more hidden layers → output layer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each connection has a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "weight",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (learned scalar). Each neuron has a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "bias",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (learned offset). For input vector "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "x",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and weights "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "w",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", the pre-activation is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "z = w · x + b",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The neuron output is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "a = f(z)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "f",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is an activation function (covered in the next topic)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Transformers—the architecture behind GPT, Claude, and most production LLMs—are deep networks of linear layers (matrix multiplications) wrapped in nonlinear activations and attention blocks. Token embeddings, feed-forward sublayers inside each transformer block, and the final vocabulary projection are all layer stacks operating on high-dimensional vectors."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When debugging model behavior, tuning fine-tuning, or reading papers, the vocabulary is layer-centric: hidden size, number of layers, width vs depth trade-offs. Without this foundation, terms like \"4096-dim hidden state\" or \"MLP expansion ratio\" remain opaque."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Single neuron"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "One neuron with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "n",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " inputs computes "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "z = Σ(w_i * x_i) + b",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", then applies activation. In matrix form, an entire layer of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "m",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " neurons is one matrix multiply: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Z = X W^T + b",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "X",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has shape "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "(batch, n)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "W",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has shape "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "(m, n)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "b",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has shape "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "(m,)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Layer types"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Input layer",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — holds raw features (token IDs converted to embeddings, pixel values, etc.); usually no learned transform at this stage"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Hidden layers",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — intermediate representations; depth here enables hierarchical feature learning"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Output layer",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — produces task-specific outputs (class logits, next-token scores over the vocabulary)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forward pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Data flows one direction: input → layer 1 → layer 2 → … → output. Each layer transforms the previous layer's activations. In a transformer block, the feed-forward network (FFN) is typically two linear layers with an activation in between—often expanding dimension (e.g., 4× hidden size) then projecting back."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# One linear layer: 768 inputs -> 3072 outputs (typical FFN expand)\nffn_expand = nn.Linear(768, 3072)\nffn_contract = nn.Linear(3072, 768)\n\nx = torch.randn(4, 768)  # batch of 4 token vectors\nhidden = torch.relu(ffn_expand(x))\nout = ffn_contract(hidden)\nprint(out.shape)  # torch.Size([4, 768])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parameters and capacity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A layer with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "n",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " inputs and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "m",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " outputs has "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "m * n + m",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " learnable parameters (weights + biases). Deeper and wider networks have more capacity to fit complex patterns but require more data, compute, and careful regularization."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Examples"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "NumPy: manual layer forward pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef layer_forward(x, W, b):\n    \"\"\"x: (n,), W: (m, n), b: (m,) -> output (m,)\"\"\"\n    z = W @ x + b\n    return np.maximum(0, z)  # ReLU activation\n\nx = np.array([1.0, 0.5, -0.2])\nW = np.random.randn(4, 3) * 0.1\nb = np.zeros(4)\n\nactivations = layer_forward(x, W, b)\nprint(activations.shape)  # (4,)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stacking layers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class TinyMLP(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, dim=64):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.layers = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(dim, 128),\n            nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(128, 64),\n            nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(64, 10),\n        )\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        return self.layers(x)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In LLM terms, each transformer layer repeats: attention sublayer (mixes token information) + FFN sublayer (two linear layers per token position). A 32-layer model applies this pattern 32 times."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Width vs depth",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — wider layers increase parameters per step; deeper stacks build more abstract representations. LLMs often favor depth (many transformer layers) with moderate width per layer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Parameter count",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — larger layers mean more GPU memory and slower inference; quantization and distillation exist partly to shrink these linear layers."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Linear-only stacks",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — without nonlinear activations between layers, multiple linear layers collapse to one; depth adds no expressiveness."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Vanishing signals",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — very deep networks without skip connections (residual links) can make early layers hard to train; transformers use residual connections around each sublayer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Confusing neurons with parameters",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — one layer has many neurons; total parameters depend on matrix dimensions, not neuron count alone."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Shape mismatches",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — output of layer L must match input width of layer L+1; off-by-one in embedding dim breaks the entire forward pass."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Forgetting bias",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — omitting bias terms reduces model flexibility; most frameworks include bias by default in nn.Linear."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Treating layers as independent",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — activations from earlier layers constrain what later layers can represent; the network is a coupled system."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Print tensor shapes during development: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "x.shape",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " after each layer catches dimension bugs early."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Start with a known baseline architecture (e.g., two-layer MLP) before scaling depth."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use framework modules ("
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "nn.Linear",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ") rather than manual loops—they are optimized and match how LLM code is written."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When reading model configs, map "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "hidden_size",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ", "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "intermediate_size",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ", and "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "num_hidden_layers",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " directly to layer dimensions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mental model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Think of each layer as a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "filter bank",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": every neuron asks a different question about the input vector (\"how much does this pattern match?\") and writes its answer into the output vector. Stacking layers lets later filters combine answers from earlier ones—edges → shapes → objects in vision; subword patterns → syntax → semantics in language."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An LLM hidden state at layer 12 is a 4096-dimensional summary of everything the network has computed about that token so far—built entirely from repeated matrix multiplies and nonlinearities."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A neuron computes weighted sum + bias, then activation; a layer is many neurons in parallel (one matrix multiply)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Transformers stack linear layers inside FFN blocks and projection heads—this is the same primitive at LLM scale."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Forward pass flows input → hidden → output; shapes must align at every boundary."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Capacity grows with width × depth; residual connections help train very deep stacks."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Reading model configs (hidden size, num layers, intermediate size) maps directly to layer geometry."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
